\section{Appendix A}

\begin{equation}
    \frac{\partial^2 F(x)}{\partial x^2} + k^2 F(x) = 0
\end{equation}

Assume that the solution, $F(x)$, will be proportional to $e^{\lambda x}$.\\
We substitute $F(x) = e^{\lambda x}$ into our equation.

\begin{equation}
    \frac{\partial^2}{\partial x^2}(e^{\lambda x}) + k^2 e^{\lambda x} = 0
\end{equation}

$\frac{\partial^2}{\partial x^2}(e^{\lambda x})$ is easy to derivate, and the solution is 

\begin{equation}
    \frac{\partial^2}{\partial x^2}(e^{\lambda x}) = \lambda^2 e^{\lambda x}
\end{equation}

we now have the equation

\begin{equation}
 \lambda^2 e^{\lambda x} + k^2 e^{\lambda x} = (\lambda^2 + k^2)  e^{\lambda x} = 0
\end{equation}

Because $e^{\lambda x}$ can never be zero, the solution to this equation must be $\lambda^2 + k^2 = 0$, so we get $\lambda = ik$ and $\lambda = -ik$.\\
This gives us

\begin{equation}
 F_1(x) = C_1 e^{ikx}
\end{equation}

and 

\begin{equation}
 F_2(x) = C_2 e^{-ikx}
\end{equation}

our general solution is 

\begin{equation}
 F(x) = C_1 e^{ikx} + C_2 e^{-ikx}
\end{equation}

If we now apply Euler's identity $e^{\alpha + i\beta} = e^{\alpha}\cos(\beta) + ie^{\alpha}\sin(\beta)$, we have $\alpha = 0$ and $\beta = \pm kx$.\\
Now we get

\begin{equation}
 F(x) = C_1(\cos(kx) + i\sin(kx)) + C_2(\cos(kx) - i\sin(kx))
\end{equation}

this can be rewritten to

\begin{equation}
 F(x) = (C_1 + C_2)\cos(kx) + i(C_1 - C_2)\sin(kx)
\end{equation}

$(C_1 + C_2)$ and $i(C_1 - C_2)$ are only some constant, and can be rewritten to som new constants $A$ and $B$ respectively.\\
The final solution to the differential equation is

\begin{equation}
 F(x) = A\cos(kx) + B\sin(kx)
\end{equation}